article.description:
Texas Tech's 81-75 loss to Missouri on Wednesday eliminated the
Lady Raiders from the Big 12 women's tournament, but Marsha Sharp thinks
her team deserves an NCAA bid.
article.headline: Mizzou to face OU in semifinals
article.linkText: Mizzou ousts Texas Tech, but Sharp wants at-large
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- Marsha Sharp has announced her intentions to
retire at the end of the season, but she isn't ready to walk away
just yet. Sharp wants to coach Texas Tech for at least one more
game -- in the NCAA tournament.

Texas Tech's 81-75 loss to Missouri on Wednesday eliminated the
Lady Raiders from the Big 12 women's tournament, but Sharp thinks
her team deserves an NCAA bid.

"The Big 12 is a good conference, and that in itself should
help us," Sharp said. "We finished fifth in the conference, we
had the sixth or seventh best strength of schedule in the country,
hopefully that will help us. A lot depends on other conference
races. Hopefully we've shown enough that we'll be in."

Tech has gone to the tournament 16 years in a row under Sharp
and has four appearances in the Elite Eight, winning the national
title in 1993.

But this year Tech is a bubble team with a 15-14 record.

"We had a whole bunch of heart," said Tech's LaToya Davis. "I
feel we should get in, but it's their choice."

If the Lady Raiders are bypassed for the NCAA tournament, the
WNIT would probably come calling. But Sharp said she was unsure if
the Lady Raiders would accept a WNIT bid.

"I don't think we've really made that decision," Sharp said.

Missouri coach Cindy Stein felt drawing Tech in the second round
of the Big 12 tourney was a no-win situation.

"We did not want to be the team to beat Texas Tech because of
Marsha Sharp," Stein said. "We think the world of her. It was a
real emotional game."

LaToya Bond scored 24 points and Tiffany Brooks added 15 to lead
Missouri.

Cristelle N'Garsanet, Carlynn Savant and EeTisha Riddle all had
11 points for the Tigers.

Fourth-seeded Missouri (21-8) meets top-seeded Oklahoma in
Thursday's semifinals.

Alesha Robertson had 17 points for Texas Tech. Erin Grant added
15 points and nine assists, and Davis also scored 15 points for the
Lady Raiders.

Texas Tech got as close as 62-58 with 8:11 left on Robertson's
3-pointer.

But Missouri went on an 8-3 run capped by Bond's layup with 3:12
remaining for a 70-61 advantage.

The Tigers maintained at least a six-point lead the rest of the
way.

Missouri held a 37-33 halftime edge behind Bond's 13 points
after Texas Tech was in front by as many as 10 over the first seven
minutes.
